issue.title: [BUG] properties of undefined error using HuggingFace Inference Embedding
issue.body: **Describe the bug** A clear and concise description of what the bug is. Some unexpected behavior in `HuggingFaceInferenceEmbedding/core#_embed` method: ```typescript async _embed(texts: string[]): Promise { // replace newlines, which can negatively affect performance. const clean = texts.map((text) => text.replace(/\n/g, ' ')) // error ``` causes ``` TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'replace') flowise-flowise-1 | at /usr/local/lib/node_modules/flowise/node_modules/flowise-components/dist/nodes/embeddings/HuggingFaceInferenceEmbedding/core.js:19:48 ``` **To Reproduce** Steps to reproduce the behavior: - Document Loader - HuggingFace Inference Embedding - In-Memory Vector Store **Expected behavior** A clear and concise description of what you expected to happen. A check before replace text. **Screenshots** If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem. **Flow** If applicable, add exported flow in order to help replicating the problem. **Setup** - Installation [e.g. docker, `npx flowise start`, `yarn start`] - **docker** - Flowise Version [e.g. 1.2.11] - **latest, i.e., 1.3.8** - OS: [e.g. macOS, Windows, Linux] - **mac osx arm64** - Browser [e.g. chrome, safari] - **chrome** **Additional context** Add any other context about the problem here.

issue.title: New Feature - Output Parsers
issue.body:
@HenryHengZJ Need your (early) feedback on this new Feature.

[Lanchain Output Parsers](https://js.langchain.com/docs/modules/model_io/output_parsers/)

Very initial (draft) implementation for handing output parsers in Flowise.

![image](https://github.com/FlowiseAI/Flowise/assets/842544/f8897092-0d46-494a-a4d4-f17faaabf231)

![image](https://github.com/FlowiseAI/Flowise/assets/842544/c3cd71fa-b0a6-4267-b1e0-469c396a9afa)

Do not spend time reviewing the code, it needs a lot of cleanup / refactoring.

comment.body:
> @vinodkiran would love to have the 1.) implemented for the next PR, so we can properly return the JSON when calling API, and this can lead to us starting to implement extraction/tagging chain - https://js.langchain.com/docs/modules/chains/popular/structured_output. What do you think?

@HenryHengZJ Agreed. Makes perfect sense. I will update this PR to return json...when will the base PR be merged?
